					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Con=
ic solid with a polygonal base</div>
<p>A <b>pyramid</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedro=
n" title=3D"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a> (a geometric figure) formed by conne=
cting a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon"=
>polygonal</a> base and a point, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Apex_(geometry)" title=3D"Apex (geometry)">apex</a>. Each base <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_(geometry)" title=3D"Edge (geom=
etry)">edge</a> and apex form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tr=
iangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle</a>, called a lateral face. A pyramid i=
s a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Cone">conic sol=
id</a> with a polygonal base. Many types of pyramids can be found by determ=
ining the shape of bases, either by based on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon" title=3D"Regular polygon">regular polygon</a>=
 (regular pyramids) or by cutting off the apex (truncated pyramid). It can =
be generalized into higher dimensions, known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Hyperpyramid" title=3D"Hyperpyramid">hyperpyramid</a>. All py=
ramids are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-dual_polyhedron" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Self-dual polyhedron">self-dual</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPyramid_(geometr=
y)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pyramid.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Pyramid=
.svg/250px-Pyramid.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"190"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"845" data-file-height=3D"641"=
></a><figcaption>Parts of a pyramid</figcaption></figure>
<p>A pyramid is a polyhedron that may be formed by connecting each vertex i=
n a planar polygon to a point lying outside that plane. This point is calle=
d the pyramid's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apex_(geometry)" t=
itle=3D"Apex (geometry)">apex</a>, and the planar polygon is the pyramid's =
base. Each other face of the pyramid is a triangle<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cromw=
ell_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyram=
id_(geometry)#cite_note-cromwell-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> consisting of one of the bas=
e's edges, and the two edges connecting that edge's endpoints to the apex. =
These faces are called the pyramid's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Lateral_surface" title=3D"Lateral surface">lateral faces</a>, and each e=
dge connected to the apex is called a lateral edge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-smit=
h_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid=
_(geometry)#cite_note-smith-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Historically, the definition of a=
 pyramid has been described by many mathematicians in ancient times. <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid_of_Alexandria" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Euclid of Alexandria">Euclides</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">El=
ements</a></i> defined a pyramid as a solid figure, constructed from one pl=
ane to one point. The context of his definition was vague until <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron_of_Alexandria" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Heron of Alexandria">Heron of Alexandria</a> defined it as the figur=
e by putting the point together with a polygonal base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-h=
eath-v3_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
yramid_(geometry)#cite_note-heath-v3-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prismatoid" title=3D"Pris=
matoid">prismatoid</a> is defined as a polyhedron where its vertices lie on=
 two parallel planes, with its lateral faces as triangles, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">trapezoids</a>, and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelo=
gram">parallelograms</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-an_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-an-4"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Pyramids are classified as prismatoid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-grunbau=
m_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid=
_(geometry)#cite_note-grunbaum-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Classification_and_types">C=
lassification and types</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DPyramid_(geometry)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"=
Edit section: Classification and types"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><div class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner=
" style=3D"width:292px;max-width:292px"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"t=
single" style=3D"width:114px;max-width:114px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" sty=
le=3D"height:106px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"htt=
