file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/0/02/Pentagonal_pyramid.png/250px-Pentagonal_pyramid.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"189" height=3D"117" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"413" data-file-height=3D"255"></a></span></div></div><div=
 class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:97px;max-width:97px"><div class=3D"thumbi=
mage" style=3D"height:116px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hexagonal_pyramid.png" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe=
dia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Hexagonal_pyramid.png/120px-Hexagonal_pyramid.png" d=
ecoding=3D"async" width=3D"95" height=3D"116" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"665" data-file-height=3D"811"></a></span></div></div></div>=
<div class=3D"trow" style=3D"display:flex"><div class=3D"thumbcaption">The =
family of a regular polygonal base pyramid: tetrahedron, square pyramid, pe=
ntagonal pyramid, and hexagonal pyramid.</div></div></div></div>
<p>The terms "right pyramid" and "regular pyramid" are used to describe spe=
cial cases of pyramids. Their common notions are as follows. A <i>regular p=
yramid</i> is one with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_p=
olygon" title=3D"Regular polygon">regular polygon</a> as its base. A <i>rig=
ht pyramid</i> is one where the axis (the line joining the centroid of the =
base and the apex) is perpendicular to the base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-o'leary=
_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_=
(geometry)#cite_note-o'leary-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mathworld_7-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geo=
metry)#cite_note-Mathworld-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bartol_8-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry=
)#cite_note-Bartol-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An <i>oblique pyramid</i> is one where the=
 axis is <i>not</i> perpendicular to the base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mathopenr=
ef_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrami=
d_(geometry)#cite_note-mathopenref-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, there are no stan=
dard definitions for these terms, and different sources use them somewhat d=
ifferently.
</p><p>Some sources define the term "right pyramid" only as a special case =
for regular pyramids,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-VNR_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-VNR-10"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> while others define it for the general case of any shape of a ba=
se. Other sources define only the term "right pyramid" to include within it=
s definition the regular base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Davies_11-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_no=
te-Davies-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Rarely, a "right pyramid" is defined to be a pyra=
mid whose base is circumscribed about a circle and the altitude of the pyra=
mid meets the base at the circle's center.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-polya_12-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geomet=
ry)#cite_note-polya-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>For the pyramid with an <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>n</i></span>-</span>sided regular base, it has <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>n</i> + 1</span> vertices, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> + 1</span>=
 faces, and <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i></span> edges.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-humble_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-humble-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such pyramid has <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isosceles_triangle" title=3D"Isoscele=
s triangle">isosceles triangles</a> as its faces, with <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramidal_symmetry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pyr=
amidal symmetry">its symmetry</a> is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>C</i><sub><=
i>n</i>v</sub></span>, a symmetry of order <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i=
></span>: the pyramids are symmetrical as they rotated around their axis of=
 symmetry (a line passing through the apex and the base centroid), and they=
 are mirror symmetric relative to any perpendicular plane passing through a=
 bisector of the base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-johnson-symmetry_14-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_=
note-johnson-symmetry-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-alexandroff_15-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geome=
try)#cite_note-alexandroff-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Examples are <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_pyramid" title=3D"Square pyramid">square pyram=
id</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_pyramid" tit=
le=3D"Pentagonal pyramid">pentagonal pyramid</a>, a four- and five-triangul=
ar faces pyramid with a square and pentagon base, respectively; they are cl=
assified as the first and second <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J=
ohnson_solid" title=3D"Johnson solid">Johnson solid</a> if their regular fa=
ces and edges that are equal in length, and their symmetries are <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>C</i><sub>4v</sub></span> of order 8 and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>C</i><sub>5v</sub></span> of order 10, respectively.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-johnson-92_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-johnson-92-16"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-uehara_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-uehara-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron" title=3D"Tetrahedron">tetrahedron=
</a> or triangular pyramid is an example that has four equilateral triangle=
s, with all edges equal in length, and one of them is considered as the bas=
e. Because the faces are regular, it is an example of a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic solid">Platonic sol=
id</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltahedra" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Deltahedra">deltahedra</a>, and it has <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedral_symmetry" title=3D"Tetrahedral symmetr=
y">tetrahedral symmetry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-shavinina_18-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_n=
ote-shavinina-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-cundy_19-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note=
-cundy-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> A pyramid with the base as <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a> is known as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Cone (geometry)"><i>cone</i></a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-kelley_20-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#=
cite_note-kelley-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Pyramids have the property of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Self-dual" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Self-dual">self-dual</a>, mean=
ing their duals are the same as vertices corresponding to the edges and vic=
e versa.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wohlleben_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-wohlleben-21"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeleton_(topology=
)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Skeleton (topology)">skeleton</a> may be =
represented as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheel_graph" ti=
tle=3D"Wheel graph">wheel graph</a>, that is they can be depicted as a poly=
gon in which its vertices connect a vertex in the center called the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_vertex" title=3D"Universal vert=
ex">universal vertex</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ps_22-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-ps-22"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:292px;max-width:292px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:143px;max-width=
:143px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:109px;overflow:hidden"><s=
pan typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Rectan=
gular_right_pyramid.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Rectangular_righ=
t_pyramid.png/250px-Rectangular_right_pyramid.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"141" height=3D"110" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"323" d=
ata-file-height=3D"251"></a></span></div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=
=3D"width:145px;max-width:145px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:=
109px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/File:Rhombic_right_pyramid.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
f/fd/Rhombic_right_pyramid.png/250px-Rhombic_right_pyramid.png" decoding=3D=
"async" width=3D"143" height=3D"110" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wi=
dth=3D"294" data-file-height=3D"226"></a></span></div></div></div><div clas=
s=3D"trow" style=3D"display:flex"><div class=3D"thumbcaption">Pyramids with=
 rectangular and rhombic bases</div></div></div></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Irregular_base"></span>A right pyramid may =
also have a base with an irregular polygon. Examples of <i>irregular pyrami=
ds</i> are those with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangle" t=
itle=3D"Rectangle">rectangle</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombus</a> as their bases. These two pyramid=
s have the symmetry of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>C</i><sub>2v</sub></span>=
 of order 4.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:292px;max-width:292px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:182px;max-width=
:182px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:103px;overflow:hidden"><s=
pan typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cono_t=
runcado.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Cono_truncado.svg/250px-Cono=
_truncado.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"180" height=3D"103" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"731" data-file-height=3D"420"></a></sp=
an></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption">A pyramid truncated by an inclined pla=
ne</div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:106px;max-width:106px">=
<div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:103px;overflow:hidden"><span type=
of=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pentagram_pyra=
mid.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.=
wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Pentagram_pyramid.png/120px-Pent=
agram_pyramid.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"104" height=3D"104" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1000" data-file-height=3D"1000"></a></=
span></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption">A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Pentagram" title=3D"Pentagram">pentagram</a>-base pyramid.</div></di=
v></div></div></div>
<p>The type of pyramids can be derived in many ways. The regularity of a py=
ramid's base may be classified based on the type of polygon: one example is=
 the <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Star_pyramid"></span><i>star pyramid</i>,=
 in which its base is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_=
star_polygon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Regular star polygon">regular =
star polygon</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wenninger_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-wenning=
er-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Truncated_pyramid"></span>The <i>trunca=
ted pyramid</i> is a pyramid cut off by a plane; if the truncation plane is=
 parallel to the base of a pyramid, it is called a <i><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" title=3D"Frustum">frustum</a></i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mensuration">Mensuration</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPyramid_(geome=
try)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Mensuration"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>The surface area is the total area of each polyhedra's faces. In the cas=
e of a pyramid, its surface area is the sum of the area of triangles and th=
e area of the polygonal base.=20
</p><p>The volume of a pyramid is the one-third product of the base's area =
and the height. The pyramid height is defined as the length of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_segment" title=3D"Line segment">line=
 segment</a> between the apex and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Orthogonal_projection" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orthogonal projec=
tion">orthogonal projection</a> on the base. Given that <span class=3D"mwe-=
math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline=
 mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w=
3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle B}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>B</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle B}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/47136aad860d145f75f3eed3022df827cee94d7a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.764ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle B}"=
></span> is the base's area and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-el=
ement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" s=
tyle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" =
alttext=3D"{\displaystyle h}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>h</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle h}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b26be3e694314bc90c3215047e4a2010c6ee184a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.339ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle h}"=
></span> is the height of a pyramid, the volume of a pyramid is:<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-ak_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_note-ak-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle V=3D{\frac {1}{3}}Bh.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>V</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mn>3</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mi>h</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle V=3D{\frac {1=
}{3}}Bh.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f978a6db7bcb8405226e701d9b96c17dd47be583" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -1.838ex; width:10.634ex; height:5.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle V=
=3D{\frac {1}{3}}Bh.}"></span>
The volume of a pyramid was recorded back in ancient Egypt, where they calc=
ulated the volume of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" ti=
tle=3D"Frustum">square frustum</a>, suggesting they were acquainted with th=
e volume of a square pyramid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gillings_25-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#cite_n=
ote-gillings-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The formula of volume for a general pyramid wa=
s discovered by Indian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Aryabhata" title=3D"Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a>, where he quoted in his <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhatiya" title=3D"Aryabhatiya"=
>Aryabhatiya</a></i> that the volume of a pyramid is incorrectly the half p=
roduct of area's base and the height.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cajori_26-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)#=
cite_note-cajori-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalization">Generalizat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPyramid_=
(geometry)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Genera=
lization"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperpyramid" title=3D"Hyperpyra=
mid">Hyperpyramid</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hyperpyramide-animation.gif" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/7/75/Hyperpyramide-animation.gif/250px-Hyperpyramide-animation.gif" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"283" data-file-height=3D"283"></a><figcaption>4-dimensional =
hyperpyramid with a cube as base</figcaption></figure>
<p>The hyperpyramid is the generalization of a pyramid in <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>-</span>dimensional space. In =
the case of the pyramid, one connects all vertices of the base, a polygon i=
n a plane, to a point outside the plane, which is the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peak_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Peak (g=
eometry)">peak</a>. The pyramid's height is the distance of the peak from t=
he plane. This construction gets generalized to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
n</i></span> dimensions. The base becomes a <span class=3D"nowrap"><span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span>-</span>polytope in a <span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span>-</span=
>dimensional hyperplane. A point called the apex is located outside the hyp=
erplane and gets connected to all the vertices of the polytope and the dist=
ance of the apex from the hyperplane is called height.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-m=
athai_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Py=
ramid_(geometry)#cite_note-mathai-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>-<=
/span>dimensional volume of a <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>n</i></span>-</span>dimensional hyperpyramid can be computed as follow=
s:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle V_{n}=3D{\frac {A\cdot h}{n}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>V</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>A</mi>
              <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
              <mi>h</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle V_{n}=3D{\fra=
c {A\cdot h}{n}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/702b38a03e05b091ad2a0be33d277119a77e98eb" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -1.838ex; width:11.916ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle V=
_{n}=3D{\frac {A\cdot h}{n}}.}"></span>
Here <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span> denotes the=
 <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>-</span>dime=
nsional volume of the hyperpyramid. <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i></span>=
 denotes the <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i>&nbsp;=
=E2=88=92&nbsp;1)</span>-</span>dimensional volume of the base and <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> the height, that is the distance between th=
e apex and the <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>n</i>&nbs=
p;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1)</span>-</span>dimensional hyperplane containing the bas=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mathai_27-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geome=
try)#cite_note-mathai-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
